# Premolars (Bicuspids)

> **Premolars** (bicuspids) are the 8 transitional teeth between canines and molars (4 upper, 4 lower), designed for **crushing and tearing** food. They are absent in deciduous dentition and only appear with permanent teeth.

## 🗂️ Types

| Type | Location | Count | Roots |
|------|----------|-------|-------|
| 1st premolars | Adjacent to canine | 4 | Upper: usually 2; Lower: 1 |
| 2nd premolars | Between 1st PM and 1st molar | 4 | 1 (both upper and lower) |

**Universal numbers:** Upper #4, #5, #12, #13 / Lower #20, #21, #28, #29

## 🔑 Key Anatomy
- **Cusps** — Two cusps (buccal + lingual/palatal) → hence "bicuspid"
- **Upper 1st premolar** — Most commonly has 2 roots (buccal + palatal) and 2 canals
- **Occlusion** — Intercuspation with opposing premolars during chewing

## 🔑 Premolar Extraction in Orthodontics
Upper first premolars are the **most commonly extracted teeth** in orthodontic treatment to create space for retracting crowded or protruding anterior teeth.

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Extraction for braces** — Upper 1st premolars commonly extracted to relieve crowding
- **Buccal furcation** — Upper 1st premolar furcation (two roots) can be difficult to clean → early periodontitis
- **Mental foramen** — Located near the apex of lower 1st–2nd premolars; risk of mental nerve injury during extraction
- **Premolar occlusion** — Premature contact here → lateral jaw deviation and TMJ strain

## 🔗 Key Connections
- [[Teeth]] — 8 of 32 permanent teeth; absent in deciduous dentition
- [[Mandible]] — lower premolars (#20, #21, #28, #29)
- [[Skull]] — upper premolars (#4, #5, #12, #13) in maxilla
- [[Cranial Nerves]] — CN V2 (upper, via middle superior alveolar nerve) + CN V3 (lower, via inferior alveolar nerve)

